SIMPLE: shadowy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shadowy
<hw>Shad"ow*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of
shade or shadows; causing shade or shadow.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Shadowy</xex> verdure.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Fenton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>shadowy</qex> desert, unfrequented woods.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, dark; obscure; gloomy; dim.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>shadowy</xex> past.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not brightly luminous; faintly light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The moon . . . with more pleasing light,⟦br⟧
<qex>Shadowy</qex> sets off the face things.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Faintly representative; hence, typical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From <qex>shadowy</qex> types to truth, from flesh to spirit.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Unsubstantial; unreal; <as>as, <ex>shadowy</ex>
honor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Milton has brought into his poems two actors of a
<qex>shadowy</qex>⟦br⟧
and fictitious nature, in the persons of Sin and Death.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shadrach</ent>⟦br⟧
